When it comes to replacing the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL without adding a new page to the navigation stack, there are two main approaches: using AJAX and using `location.replace`.

### AJAX

AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) is a technique for updating a web page without reloading the entire page. Here's how you can use AJAX to replace the contents of a page:

```javascript
// Send a GET request to the new URL
fetch('https://example.com/new-page')
  .then(response => response.text())
  .then(html => {
    // Replace the contents of the current page with the new HTML
    document.getElementById('page-content').innerHTML = html;
  })
  .catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));
```

In this example, the `fetch` API is used to send a GET request to the new URL. The response is then used to update the contents of the current page by replacing the `innerHTML` of an element with the ID `page-content`.

